Metrics You Can Actually Get (No Scraping)
1. Cuisine Category (Highest Impact) 🥩🥗
Yelp gives you this for free. Map it directly to carbon intensity — this alone accounts for the biggest variance between restaurants:
Vegan / Vegetarian     → very low  🟢
Mediterranean / Japanese → low     🟢
Seafood                → low-med   🟡
Pizza / Italian        → medium    🟡
American / Burgers     → high      🟠
BBQ / Steakhouse       → very high 🔴
Backed by FAO data — cuisine type is the single strongest predictor of food carbon footprint.
2. NYC Energy Grade (Building Efficiency) ⚡
From NYC Open Data (LL84 benchmarking). Tells you how energy-efficient the building is. Free, public, covers all large buildings.
3. Price Range (Portion/Ingredient Quality Proxy) 💰
Yelp gives you $ to $$$$. Counterintuitively:

$ fast food → high processed meat, high waste
$$$$ fine dining → smaller portions, often higher quality sourcing

Not perfect but a defensible signal.
4. Yelp Categories / Attributes 🏷️
Yelp returns tags like:

"vegan_options" → positive signal
"organic" → positive
"sustainable" → positive
"good_for_groups" → proxy for high volume/waste

These are boolean flags, easy to score.
5. Health Inspection Score 🏥
NYC Open Data has this. A proxy for operational quality — restaurants that handle food well tend to waste less.
6. Restaurant Age / Longevity 📅
Older, established restaurants tend to have more stable supply chains and less food waste than high-turnover spots. Yelp gives you date_opened.

Recommended Scoring Formula (No Scraping)
Green Score (0-100) =

  45%  Cuisine category carbon weight     ← biggest signal
  20%  NYC energy grade                   ← building efficiency  
  15%  Yelp sustainability attributes     ← vegan, organic flags
  10%  Price range proxy                  ← portion/sourcing signal
  10%  Health inspection score            ← operational quality
